data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code has three patterns from the skill inventory:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with rollback | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Continues loop after abort | Check `IsCancellationRequested` to decide |

## Why This Must Change

On .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it **will not** terminate the thread. `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown, so your catch block never runs, meaning `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` becomes dead code. Your `Stop()` method would wait 2 seconds then crash.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work, same as
                // the old ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we simply continue to the loop
                // condition, which will exit because the token is cancelled.
                // If you wanted to continue processing (like ResetAbort did),
                // you would use a per-item CancellationTokenSource instead.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation (replaces Thread.Abort)

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. Unlike .NET Framework, we cannot
            // force-kill it. Log a warning — see "Uncooperative code" below.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();  // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always dispose
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `volatile bool _running` → `CancellationTokenSource`**
The token unifies the "should I stop?" flag with the ability to wake up blocking calls. `volatile bool` can't interrupt a blocked `GetNextItem()`.

**2. `Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`**
Cooperative, not preemptive. The thread must *check* the token — cancellation won't be injected mid-instruction.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (...)`**
The `when` filter ensures you only catch cancellation *you* triggered, not unrelated `OperationCanceledException`s from other sources.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed**
No equivalent needed. After catching `OperationCanceledException`, execution continues normally (into `finally`, then the loop condition).

**5. `Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))`**
`Join` actually waits for the thread to exit rather than blindly sleeping. This was a bug in the original code — the sleep didn't guarantee the thread had stopped.

## Critical Pitfall: Blocking Calls Must Accept the Token

Your `GetNextItem()` comment says "may block." If it blocks indefinitely (e.g., on a queue or socket), **cancellation will never take effect** because cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. You must update it:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — wakes up when cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` wraps a synchronous call that doesn't accept a token (e.g., raw socket read), replace it with an async overload or use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` to poll.

## If You Need ResetAbort-Like Behavior (Continue Processing)

The original code called `ResetAbort()` to keep the loop alive after an abort. If you want to cancel one *item* but continue the loop, use a per-item token:

```csharp
while (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(parentToken);
    itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout

    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(parentToken);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Item timed out, but parent is still running — roll back and continue
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
}
```

